### @layer

**@layer** controls the cascade order by grouping styles into layers.

---

### Why Use Layers?

Without layers, **specificity** determines which style wins. Layers let you define **priority order**:

```css
/* Order: reset < components < utilities */
@layer reset, components, utilities;
```

Later layers win over earlier layers, regardless of specificity.

---

### Defining Layers

```css
/* Declare layer order first */
@layer reset, base, components, utilities;

/* Add styles to layers */
@layer reset {
  * { margin: 0; padding: 0; }
}

@layer base {
  body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; }
}

@layer components {
  .card { padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; }
}

@layer utilities {
  .text-center { text-align: center; }
}
```

---

### Layer Order

```css
@layer reset, base, components, utilities;

/* Later = higher priority */
/* utilities > components > base > reset */
/* Any style in 'utilities' beats 'components' regardless of specificity */
```

---

### Anonymous Layers

```css
@layer {
  /* Styles added to an unnamed layer */
  /* These come after named layers */
  .fallback { color: red; }
}
```

---

### Nesting in Layers

```css
@layer components {
  @layer forms {
    input { border: 1px solid #ddd; }
  }

  @layer cards {
    .card { background: white; }
  }
}

/* Nested layers are joined: components.forms, components.cards */
```

---

### Layer with @import

```css
@import url('reset.css') layer(reset);
@import url('bootstrap.css') layer(framework);
@import url('custom.css') layer(overrides);
```

---

### !important in Layers

`!important` still works but within layers:

```css
@layer base {
  p { color: blue !important; }
}

@layer components {
  p { color: red !important; } /* Wins - later layer */
}
```

---

> **Best Practice:** Use layers to organize CSS and control override priority. This is especially useful with third-party CSS.
